reviewText:
expatriate: Residing in a different country while maintaining citizenship of your native homeland.

An enjoyable high octane action flick utilizing a cookie-cutter screenplay. Yes, it is a formula product, but surprisingly even productions that rip from the blueprint often screw up. Having been able to, at the very least, overcome the astounding amount of inane and worthless flicks that populate the cinematic landscape nowadays is in itself a success. This tracked true to the recipe, so I would categorize it as very solid.

Preface caveat: Aaron Eckart is one of those performers that I seemingly cannot connect with on any level. He has all the hallmarks of a quality actor - projection, presence, and personality. Yet for all those talents - I can't seem to find common ground. And I honestly can't explain why.

That said, I found his performance in this production surprisingly engaging and quite entertaining. Hopefully it's a trend.

In 'Expatriate' he plays Ben Logan, tech security specialist. Hired by a global security company for his expertise - breaking into previously thought of unhackable systems - exposing vulnerabilities, weaknesses and flaws in their product lines.

To showcase his level of commitment to the company, Ben chooses to stay overseas in order to work at the Belgian offices of the corporation. Along with him is his young daughter Amy, although she isn't nearly as pleased with her new status as an expatriate. But the death of her mother back in the states left no other choice. Having had little contact with her father since birth, the incongruent pair are just now learning to adjust to one another; her dad's comfortable paycheck acting as a stable platform for their fresh start, making the transition bearable.

Until the day that his company literally disappears.

Everyone he knew is gone. The office he has been going to daily for the past six months is stripped bare, his fellow employees vanished. Everything a modern person uses to define a life no longer exists for Logan - no bank account, no money, no digital records, no identification, nothing. Not even his cell phone, which is company property, works anymore. His existence has been erased.

Just what's going on?

As father and daughter are caught up in a bizarre and terrifying world of espionage and twisted corporate shadows, they're forced on the run. With little or no break, they have to stay one step in front of professional assassins and various spy agencies looking to put them into a set of anonymous graves.

There were some weaknesses in the film that have to be acknowledged.

Young co-star Liana Liberato's character as Amy was often artificially too self-aware. For someone who projected typical adolescent immaturity at the beginning of the film, to then flip a switch and become a strong and emotionally composed character - i.e. The driving sequence/interrogation - was ridiculous. And certain aspects of the script rang false; particularly when the intelligence officers gather to discuss the true situation of Ben Logan.

Still, those minor criticisms were mostly forgivable when balanced out with the enjoyable heart-thumping pace of the movie.

Overall, you'll enjoy this if you can imagine Jason Bourne with a kid.
I was kind of bummed out that I was not able to get dvd to play on my dvd player, but was able to view movie through my laptop. I am a big fan of Aaron Eckhart so the purchase was very worth it.
An ex-CIA agent is forced on the run when his employer marks him for termination.  Wow!! What an Action Ride/ On the Edge/ Intense/ Shooting/ Fighting/ Explosions / You Get it All....

Ben Logan (Aaron Eckhart) works for a security testing company in Belgium.  His teen daughter, Amy (Liana Liberato)attends high school. One day when Ben goes to work he finds out his company is missing and never existed.

Being a former CIA agent, Ben investigates. He ends up on the lam battling the CIA, authorities, and a corporation that all want him and his daughter dead. Amy quickly goes from a snarky teen to Internet sleuth.

The film consists of a lot of double agents. The twists are shown to the audience which takes away from any mystery aspect. It is the "Bourne" type of film with one man against the system. This one has the addition of a daughter.

This is a fairly decent film for those who like the "Bourne" type of film, especially if your thirst was not satisfied with that latest 4th "Bourne" installment.

The reason why I rated it so low was because the story was a deviation of the original anime, which by the way deviates from the manga; but the conclusion is really unsatisfactory, unlike the anime or the manga because in them the culprit is cleverly caught, while the way the culprit is caught in the movie is... well... idiotic in my opinion.

Anyways, if you haven't seen the anime or read the manga I would suggest it because the whole concept of going back to time is usually appealing but don't expect too much for the ending

However, when the person that is trying to keep you alive, especially if that person is a parent with some skills, maybe showing a little more respect and a little less indignation might be on the agenda.  I am tired of watching movies that show kids acting and talking to adults, especially their parents, in any type of fashion as if that is acceptable.  (Spoiler Alert) Really, in the middle of a get-away, I am going to drive recklessly, fast as hell down a narrow street almost killing us both because I want my daddy to tell me who that bad, bad lady is... right now!!!  Come on!!!  Yeah, with killers breathing down our necks, now is the time for teenage angst and rebellion.  Again, enjoyed the rental, but, please, no more movies with smart mouth kids on the run with their parents from assassins.  Leave the kid(s) with the grandparents, uncle, aunt or somebody!!!  Now I have to watch some Jason Bourne movies to get that particular madness out of my head.

Its sort of like Jason Bourne meets 'The Net' (the so-so Sandra Bullock movie from years back) anyway, due to how far hacking has evolved over the years---its a bit more believable than 'The Net'.
I gave it 4 stars as the action was pretty good---I would have given it 5 stars, but the plot prevented it.  The story goes that Aaron Eckhart's character is an ex-CIA agent who was clueless about the dubious dealings of the company he's been working at for the past few years.  Now, I have a hard time buying this...if this guy was as well trained as say, a Jason Bourne type, how could he NOT notice stuff about his co-workers??  I mean in 'The Bourne Identity' Jason had the mother-of-all brain-wipes after he was shot in the opening scene---and he spotted little things like a guy at the counter could handle himself in a fight & a bunch of other little things about total strangers.
Yes, I realize this isn't 'The Bourne Identity' but it was the closest movie to compare this one to.
As I said, the action is pretty good---not TOO hoaky as these movies can go. If you can get past the obvious plot hole I mentioned above---its a fairly decent popcorn & chill movie.

The movie has an interesting plot, but it's downfall is the sub-plot concerning the main character's  family. Every time things start to get interesting, the main character's teenage daughter steals the show with her unending whining. Eckhart's character does everything a father could possibly do for a daughter under the circumstances, including risking his life several times for her's, yet she looks at him like he's the villain. The disrespectful snarkiness she shows her father only slows them both down as they run for their lives, and slows down the plot, as well. I also disliked the bit of sexism thrown in at the midway point concerning a female CIA agent whose reputation is marred by who she's slept with. Can't she just be a CIA agent??? Typical Hollywood.

Three and a half MYSTERIOUS Stars! "Erased" is a European-based spy drama that rushes headlong through Belgium cities and other places. The opening scene is a daring robbery and transfer of the stolen items. Then the scene switches to Aaron Eckhart's character who is leading a normal life as a dad of a teenage daughter and an engineer. But without warning, parts of his identity are wiped out and other disappearances take place as the true creepy plot begins to unfold. His daughter is also drawn into the caper. And the central question is "why is all of this is taking place" once the great reveal occurs? But, at least, this is not yet another 'run of the mill' "save the world from the bad guys as the clock counts down" plot, although there are lots of shoot outs and it gets gory at times. Beyond this, the acting is very good, but the overall plot could have been better. Starring Aaron Eckhart (The Dark Knight, Battle LA), Olga Kurylenko (Quantum of Solace, Oblivion), Liana Liberato, Yassine Fadel, Garrick Hagon, David Bark-Jones, and Ronnie Commissaris. Directed by Philipp Stolzl. Definitely Recommended for spy genre buffs. Three and a half INTRIGUING Stars. (Amazon Instant Video. E-Motion/Expatriat Films. Rated R. Color. CC. X-Ray. Time-1:44:34.)

I didn't expect much when I started the movie rolling on my desktop. The descriptive blurb screamed "direct to video" to anyone who cared to read it. The plot is, of course, unlikely and requires a pretty hefty suspension of disbelief. The character cliches of a tough but vulnerable, slightly shady but heart-of-gold, spy come in from the cold, corrupt CIA agents and black-hearted, nearly impossibly evil corporate psychopaths are all there for the movie's writers to work with.

On the positive side, the plot flows very smoothly, the writing is adequate, the acting is above average, the cinematography good, the unlikely McGuffen is easy to understand, and the background environment is a little different than most other European locations. Altogether a good effort to put together an amusing and fast paced action movie to waste away an hour or two on a cold and rainy Autumn night.

I frankly only noticed Erased because of the blatant attempt to evoke "Taken", but no regrets about passing an afternoon with this somewhat generic action pic.  On a dramatic level this film is certainly no "must see", but Aaron Eckhart gives us a good and charismatic performance as the action hero, and the production quality on the action level is very good.

SPOILERS MAY FOLLOW!  The following just delves a little into criticism.  The performance of the daughter, Amy, was quite all right, but the scripting of this part was often a bore.  Yes, we can enjoy empathizing with the true qualities of the father daughter roles, but in this type of fiction I probably wanted a little less common of a teenage girl.  Does anyone else remember the Walmart family night feature films?  Amy would have been right at home in one of those "family value" plots, touching upon the self assured side, the pouty, the know it all, and the "deal with me as I step on the gas pedal which would in reality kill us in haste" scene.

SPOILERS DO FOLLOW!  If there was a breaking point in the dramatic aspect, for me it was in that escape from the hotel garage CIA shootout confrontation.  In the earlier vehicle escape scene I felt real concern for who may or may not be killed or maimed, but this time as Amy sped down the avenue, after a moment each long passing second my interest waned.  This was not Jason Bourne skillfully dodging collision, but Amy on the drag strip defying dad way beyond the likely survivability no more than if she had been texting on the freeway.  And if we forgive the extension of that little scene, what happens next? This movie starts off kind of rocky with the director apparently attempting to convey as many passing. The opening 5-10 minutes are like you're window shopping at Chekhov's Gun Store. Every little tiny bit of information in that opening will be referenced again. After the movie brushes off the weird intro and starts to find itself, it's a decent enough romp...aside from the fact that nobody besides Aaron Eckhart can act. (Olga Kurylenko is TERRIBLE in this movie. She can barely get her lines out. The rest of the cast aren't any better.)

The movie was going along decently enough until just about the midpoint, and at that point, I guess the screenwriter was rushed for time or something, because there's not a single sensible move that anyone else in the movie makes from that point forward. Amy, the daughter vacillates between competent and dumb as a rock or steely and weepy depending on what the plot requires to move forward. She's not a character, she's just a plot device. Aaron Eckhart's character just waltzes past security to accost people, nobody says a word. Even the big bad doesn't make any sense. The are just too many nonsensical moving parts in the latter half.

(Warning: maybe a spoiler here or two).  A decent enough thriller, but lots and lots -- and lots -- of plot holes which really detract from it. The basic premise is a bit thin to start with. The business of the bad guys who are just freakin' supermen at finding someone who wants to be lost in a big city is dubious enough. Or bad guys casually wandering through a modern European city slaughtering people right and left -- never a cop in sight, not until the good guy is dizzily climbing from a smashed car or trying to escape through a crowd, anyhow -- really stretches it. (I mean, really, a guy runs into a hospital gunning down anyone in his way: doctors, nurses, patients asleep in their beds, visitors? Describing that as over the top is like calling the Grand Canyon deep).  And you have to love an ending where the hero, having conquered all, is able to prance happily through an airport onto a plane. What happened to all the all-points bulletins with Interpol that were out for him? They magically died with the bad guys? Still, if you're good at suspending disbelief, it's sort of a kick to watch, with a reasonably satisfying ending.

If you enjoy espionage flicks, with plenty of non-stop action...this is the one. Aaron Eckhart's perfect for this part. He's an ex covert operative for the US, who has quit his American spy job. Now he lives & works in Europe. His teenage daughter lives with him, but wishes she was back stateside with her grandfather again. He's been hired by a Security Company, to find weak spots in their security systems. To try to defeat their "security inventions"...so they can be retooled & improved upon. One day he finds a discrepancy with a "part number" in one of the devices he was inspecting. This discovery winds up turning his whole world upside down. He literally becomes a nobody from that point on. His identity has been "Erased". He gets blamed for things he didn't do...or incidents that "did" happen...but were well beyond his control. Without revealing anything further...why not pick this one to watch. I enjoyed it. As did my family members who watched it with me.

If you suddenly wake up some day and the company that you work for no longer exists then, hopefully, you are ex-CIA (like Aaron Eckhart aka Ben Logan in Erased) so you might be able to unravel what happened. Of course, while doing all of the, as it turns out, dangerous investigation, it doesn't help that your estranged daughter (Liana Liberato aka Amy Logan) now happens to live with you and that you are finding dead co-workers everywhere and that a colleague, Anna Brandt (Olga Kurylenko), may not be providing you will good intel. As thrillers (not mysteries) go, this is a bit predictable at times but overall there is enough good action and suspense mixed in to the (not overly original) plot and sub-plots to keep one entertained. It is definitely above average (or what is called "okay" at 3), especially with Eckhart and Kurylenko, so I'll round it up to 4.

Excellent cinematography and editing along with good directing by Philipp Stlzl make for a spy thriller with flair. The plot is of the somewhat overdone "spy who tries to leave the game but becomes a target" genre, but it includes some superior elements, including the very believable father-daughter relationship. Sticklers for accuracy might quibble over some details (such as making plastique in the kitchen) but these are not at the heart of the story. For once, the European setting is authentic rather than just a stage backdrop, and the viewer is transported into genuinely foreign environments. I liked it well enough to give it a 4.5 but not a 5-star rating.

Critics panned Erased for being derivative, and it is. But if you have a working formula and can tell it again with suspense and drama, where's the harm? Erased is your basic thriller with actors and crew I've never heard of doing admirable work. There are a few places where believability is stretched thin (cars aren't that easy to hotwire nor are deadbolts that easy to pick). But pacing is excellent, plot twists are well timed, character development is credible (I thought I would hate the generic Amy Logan, played by Liana Liberato, but she turned out to be un-generic and I loved her), and the music is great. Critics also carped about scenes supposedly set in Brussels that were clearly filmed in Antwerp; that's just snooty scribes showing off their Euro knowledge. No one barks when something supposedly occurring in Montana is shot in Canada. Executive summary: if you like intense thrillers, you'll love Erased.

I nominate the Tek 9 for an Oscar. Who agrees with me that guns should appear in the credits? It so often seems that guns play such a prominent role in movies that they become a crutch for suspense. Now that shooting people is so commonplace in movies, for greater impact producers must think they have to show scores of people being shot, using a variety of guns and camera angles. In other respects, the movie was average, with good production values, but the plot begs the audience to ignore the notion that a CIA hit man (is that really a thing?) is traipsing around Europe on a job WITH HIS DAUGHTER IN TOW, while on the payroll of a company, and with people, that he only decides to check out after events get out of control. I often felt I was too old to be watching the movie - that the target audience is teenagers, but I wouldn't let my kids see this film. The scenes of violence are gratuitous and unnecessary, and the plot is flaccid and unchallenging.

I really like Aaron Eckhart, and I loved Taken - the obvious inspiration of "Erased." However, the movie is badly let down by its script. If you come here to see a revenge movie (as which the movie clearly markets itself), don't. Its focus is on how poor immigrants suffer from the evil of the (American) White Man, presented with the subtlety and intelligence of an agitprop movie.

Part of what worked in Taken was that Liam Neeson was both likable, and credible as an experienced fighting machine. Eckhart's father is written - by an (ethnic) non-American - as a dumb cliche of the American Man: he lives in beautiful Europe, and all he can think of to do with his daughter is to watch baseball; and he feeds her nuts and so almost kills her despite an allergy that *a CIA agent living to be extremely detail-oriented* would have taken due note of. Contrary to the calm resolve of Neeson, Eckhart is hurried and hunted and out of breath the entire friggin movie.

The few fights are like 50s Western: two guuuuuuys hitting each other over and over, but no one breaks even as much as a finger or bites or scratches which, if you did any contact sport, you know is the kind of thing you go for. There is one fight that turns a bit more decisive, but overall, the fights are a true bore and not realistic in the least. And after, as the daughter stays with Daddy, it's always "I'm so sorry, daughter!" times. The movie targets the middle-class that used to be busy protesting Bush's wars as its ample trite social commentary shows, delivering the interracial happy ending (between the daughter and some guy you saw briefly 3 times before) that you, I am sure, were so waiting for.

What it doesn't deliver, is thrills or even logic.

Just think, she's the smartest person in the movie even though her high school report card showed mostly grades of C and D.  Yuk. It helps to know the following from the outset as you watch this interesting movie.

A CIA manager working secretly for the bad-guys; hires experts, who have worked as consultants for the CIA in the past, to build small containers with coded access, which will eventually hold secret CIA documents. This is so the bad-guys can get to the documents without the documents self destructing within their special containers, when mishandled by the wrong people. The bad CIA manager gives the bad-guys the security layout for the facility where the secret documents are stored. The bad-guys go to all this expense and trouble, because they have to retrieve a certain set of documents, which, when studied, will expose their criminal operation and eventually the moles in the CIA.

The good-guy, electronics expert, thinks he is doing normal contract work for the CIA, but comes across an odd thing and without any suspicion begins an investigation to answer some questions he has. Once he finds the answers to his questions; he will discover the project is run by bad-guys, so, before that happens, the bad-guys abruptly shut everything down.

 Once the secret documents are stolen; this good-guy, expert, who designed the sophisticated document containers, becomes a prime suspect.
